# Runbook: Rootless Solace PubSub+ on Podman + systemd (single node)

**Purpose:** stand up one Solace PubSub+ Enterprise broker as a **rootless** podman
container, supervised by a **systemd --user** unit, on a hardened RHEL VM. This is
the proven recipe from node 1 (`myhost01`). Run it as-is on VM2 and VM3 to get each
to the same standalone-green state. **HA/redundancy is NOT in this runbook** — that's
a separate pass after all three nodes are independently green.

**End state:** broker `Up`, SEMP returns HTTP 200, unit `enabled` + linger on
(survives reboot), `podman exec` works.

---

## Environment facts (this deployment)

| Thing | Value |
|---|---|
| Service user | `solace` (uid 5011, has `/bin/bash`, real shell) |
| Admin login | `appadmintemp` (sudo → root; **cannot** `sudo -u solace` — AD/Centrify run-as block) |
| Image | `artifactory.global.<corp>.com/gv-images-products/oss/solace-pubsub-enterprise:10.25.0.217` |
| podman graphroot | `/app/solace/podman/graphroot` (relocated — needs SELinux relabel) |
| podman runroot | `/app/solace/podman/runroot` |
| subuid/subgid (solace) | `755360:65536` (already allocated) |
| cgroup | v2 (`cgroup2fs`) — already correct, no reboot needed |

---

## Prerequisites (assumed already true on each VM)

- VM hardened, podman installed, `solace` user exists with `/bin/bash` and a subuid range.
- cgroup v2 active: `stat -fc %T /sys/fs/cgroup` → `cgroup2fs`.
- You reach the VM by SSH as `appadmintemp`, then `sudo -i` → `su - solace`.

If any of those differ on VM2/VM3, stop and reconcile before proceeding.

---

## Procedure

### Step 1 — Substrate (as `appadmintemp` → `sudo -i`)

```bash
# 1a. linger so solace's user manager runs without an active login (survives reboot)
loginctl enable-linger solace

# 1b. raise the USER MANAGER's limit ceiling — rootless containers cannot exceed it.
#     Solace POST requires hard nofile = 1048576; memlock must be unlimited.
mkdir -p /etc/systemd/system/user@.service.d
cat > /etc/systemd/system/user@.service.d/solace-limits.conf <<'EOF'
[Service]
LimitNOFILE=1048576
LimitMEMLOCK=infinity
LimitCORE=infinity
EOF
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl restart user@5011.service     # 5011 = solace uid

# 1c. verify the ceiling is REAL (this is the check that matters)
systemctl show user@5011.service -p LimitNOFILE -p LimitMEMLOCK
#   want: LimitNOFILE=1048576  LimitMEMLOCK=infinity
```

### Step 2 — SELinux relabel of the relocated graphroot (as root)

The graphroot was moved off the default `~/.local/share/containers`. Without the
matching SELinux label, the container's libraries can't be made executable
("cannot change memory protections"). Relabel it:

```bash
semanage fcontext -a -e /var/lib/containers /app/solace/podman/graphroot
restorecon -R -v /app/solace/podman/graphroot
semanage fcontext -a -e /var/lib/containers /app/solace/podman/runroot
restorecon -R -v /app/solace/podman/runroot

# verify — must show container_var_lib_t
ls -laZd /app/solace/podman/graphroot
```

### Step 3 — Enter solace's real session (as root → solace)

`machinectl` is not installed here, and `su -` under Centrify does not set the
session vars, so export them by hand every time you enter:

```bash
su - solace
export XDG_RUNTIME_DIR=/run/user/5011
export DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS=unix:path=/run/user/5011/bus
systemctl --user is-system-running     # running/degraded = good; "Failed to connect to bus" = stop
```

(These two exports are also in `~/.bashrc`, but export manually — don't rely on it.)

### Step 4 — Place files (as solace)

Copy `solace-compose.yml` and `solace.service` (below) into place. Files staged in
`/tmp` by appadmintemp via scp from the laptop.

```bash
mkdir -p ~/solace/storage-group ~/.config/systemd/user
cp /tmp/solace-compose.yml ~/solace/solace-compose.yml
cp /tmp/solace.service     ~/.config/systemd/user/solace.service
```

### Step 5 — Start via the user manager (as solace)

```bash
podman pull artifactory.global.<corp>.com/gv-images-products/oss/solace-pubsub-enterprise:10.25.0.217
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now solace.service
```

### Step 6 — Verify (as solace)

```bash
# broker process limits (read via host PID — avoids podman exec quirks)
cat /proc/$(podman inspect -f '{{.State.Pid}}' solace)/limits | grep -iE 'open files|locked memory'
#   want: Max open files ... 1048576 ;  Max locked memory ... unlimited

# POST must pass — look for "Determining platform type: [ OK ]", NO "POST Violation [022]"
podman logs solace 2>&1 | grep -iE 'POST|platform type'

# management plane up
curl -s -u admin:admin http://localhost:8080/SEMP/v2/monitor/about/api
#   want: ...\"responseCode\":200...

# survives reboot?
systemctl --user is-enabled solace.service    # enabled
loginctl show-user solace -p Linger           # Linger=yes
```

If SEMP returns 200 and POST shows `[ OK ]`, **this node is done.**

